{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 16:17:26.846033", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and intent\n- Topology: 2-tier Clos with EBGP throughout. Hosts: pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2/24 via leaf_router_0_0), pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2/24 via leaf_router_0_1).\n- Goal: Assess network health, detect anomalies, localize faults, and identify root cause(s). No remediation proposed.\n\nSummary of findings\n- Control-plane (BGP) across the fabric is healthy: super-spine and leaves have established BGP sessions and have learned all expected /24 host routes.\n- Data-plane issue is isolated to host pc_0_0. It cannot reach off-subnet destinations and shows “Network is unreachable.” Its local L2 connectivity to its leaf gateway is present but intermittent in first ping due to ARP resolution; subsequent reachability works.\n- Host pc_0_1 appears healthy from an L3 perspective (correct default route, successful connectivity to its leaf and other subnets via the fabric).\n\nEvidence and details\n\nFabric control-plane\n- Super-spine BGP state (AS 65000): All 8 peers Established; routes to all leaf /24s present.\n  - Example: B>* 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.7; B>* 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7; and 10.1.x/24 via 172.16.0.9.\n- Leaf routers:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (10.0.0.1/24 on eth4) has BGP Established to 4 neighbors; routes show:\n    - 10.0.0.0/24 connected on eth4 (host subnet)\n    - Other 10.0.x/24 via uplinks (e.g., via 172.16.0.56)\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (10.0.1.1/24 on eth4) similarly shows proper BGP adjacencies; 10.0.1.0/24 connected and other /24s via uplinks.\n- Conclusion: BGP and routing within the Clos fabric are in a good state; no anomalies found in the routers.\n\nHost-level data-plane tests\n- pc_0_0:\n  - Ping to pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2) fails with “Network is unreachable.”\n  - Local gateway reachability:\n    - pc_0_0 -> 10.0.0.1: 2 sent, 1 received (first packet typically lost during ARP resolution; second succeeds).\n    - leaf_router_0_0 -> 10.0.0.2: 2 sent, 1 received (consistent with initial ARP/neighbor state).\n  - ARP/NDP on leaf for host: 10.0.0.2 lladdr ... STALE (normal after inactivity; transitions on traffic).\n  - Interface and routing on pc_0_0:\n    - Interface eth0 configured 10.0.0.2/24 and up (ip link shows UP/LOWER_UP; ifconfig shows UP,RUNNING).\n    - Critically, routing table has only 10.0.0.0/24; no default route is present.\n    - This directly explains “Network is unreachable” for off-subnet destinations (e.g., 10.0.1.0/24).\n  - Note: ethtool reported “Link detected: no” once, but ip link reports LOWER_UP, and successful L2 pings to gateway were observed; this discrepancy is likely an artifact of the virtual interface reporting rather than a persistent physical link issue.\n- pc_0_1:\n  - Interface eth0 up with 10.0.1.2/24 and default route via 10.0.1.1.\n  - Can reach its leaf and, via the fabric, other subnets (as indicated by multiple lab pings showing success towards 10.0.1.2 from other hosts).\n  - Ping to 172.16.0.35 (leaf’s inter-router interface) succeeds via default gateway. Ping to 172.16.0.33 returns “Destination Net Unreachable” from 10.0.1.1 (expected, since 172.16.x/31 transit links are not globally routed to hosts).\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Host pc_0_0 lacks a default route. This is abnormal compared to pc_0_1 (which has default via its leaf).\n- Intermittent initial packet loss between pc_0_0 and 10.0.0.1/leaf, consistent with ARP neighbor resolution rather than ongoing packet loss.\n\nFault localization\n- The fault is localized to host pc_0_0 configuration (L3 stack), not the fabric.\n  - Routers have correct connectivity and routing.\n  - Leaf-router-facing interface to pc_0_0 is up; ARP entry exists.\n  - pc_0_0’s kernel has no route to non-local subnets.\n\nRoot cause\n- Misconfiguration on pc_0_0: Missing default route to its leaf gateway (10.0.0.1). This prevents any off-subnet communication and leads to “Network is unreachable” errors.\n- The one-off ethtool “Link detected: no” reading appears inconsistent with ip link and successful traffic; no evidence of persistent link failure. The observed single-packet losses are attributable to ARP neighbor resolution on first probe.\n\nOverall network health assessment\n- Fabric control-plane and inter-router forwarding: Healthy.\n- Leaf-to-host connectivity: Healthy for pc_0_1; nominal for pc_0_0 at L2 with expected ARP behavior.\n- End-to-end reachability: Impacted only for pc_0_0 due to missing default route; pc_0_1 unaffected.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13196, "output_tokens": 4391, "total_tokens": 17587, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12672}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3136}}}
